1. Structure using HTML

The foundation of the webpage is created using HTML. It defines the layout and different sections of the interface:

Navbar: Contains the logo and navigation links such as Home, Movies, TV Shows, and My Stuff.
Hero Section: Displays a featured movie banner with a title, description, and a play button.
Movie Sections: Includes categories like “Recommended for You” and “Continue Watching,” each containing multiple movie cards.

HTML ensures that all elements are properly organized and accessible.

 2. Styling using CSS

CSS is used to enhance the visual appearance of the webpage:

Dark Theme: A background color similar to streaming platforms is applied for a cinematic feel.
Flexbox Layout: Used to align movie cards in horizontal rows with smooth scrolling.
Hover Effects: Movie cards slightly enlarge when hovered over, improving user interaction.
Typography & Spacing: Proper font sizes, margins, and padding are used for readability and clean design.

CSS transforms the basic structure into a modern and attractive UI.

 3. Functionality using JavaScript

JavaScript adds dynamic behavior to the webpage:

Movie Data Storage: Movie names and images are stored in arrays.
Dynamic Rendering: JavaScript loops through the movie data and creates movie cards automatically.
Reusable Function: A function is used to display movies in different sections, making the code efficient and scalable.

This reduces manual work and allows easy updates to content.

 4. User Experience Features

The interface is designed to mimic real-world streaming platforms:

Smooth horizontal scrolling for browsing content
Interactive hover animations
Clear categorization of content
Simple and intuitive navigation
 5. Responsiveness (Optional Enhancement)

The layout can be further improved using media queries to ensure it works well on mobile devices, tablets, and desktops.

